    "## <span style=\"color:blue\"> 1. Basic Features\n",
    "\n",
    "Python is a high-level language, which means that the operating system will not execute our program instructions directly.\n",
    "\n",
    "In order for it to be executed, it must first be compiled or interpreted using compiler or interpreter. Python Kernnel will interpret the instructions so that they can be executed.\n",
    "\n",
    "![Captura de pantalla 2023-10-03 165751.png](attachment:1f5856de-f887-43c4-9eb1-25266f77fa83.png)\n",
    "\n",
    "When compiling a program written in a high-level language, a file with an executable file extension is generated (for instance in Windows .exe file will be generated). This file can be executed by any computer that has the same operating system. Although it does not have the compiler, since the instructions are specific to the processor.\n",
    "\n",
    "When it is interpreted, that file is not constructed, so it can only be executed if the interpreter is installed."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## <span style=\"color:blue\"> 2. First program in Python\n",

    "## <span style=\"color:blue\"> 3. Types of Errors\n",
    "\n",
    "![image.png](attachment:47761545-a60a-4c8b-a708-7e301050e473.png)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "<b> Print </b> function displays the specified message to the screen, or other standard output device. The message can be a string, or any other object, the object will be converted into a string before written to the screen.\n",
    "\n",
    "In addition <b> Print </b> can also be used to print the results of operations. See examples in the following cell \n",
    "\n"

    "### <span style=\"color:green\">We have an exception.</span>\n",
    "\n",
    "No syntactical errors, however the code has not been executed successfully.\n",
    "\n",
    "### <span style=\"color:green\">Keep paying attention to details</span>\n",
    "\n",
    "The interpreter has correctly executed the first three lines, as you can see the output results.\n",
    "\n",
    "There is an arrow indicating the line that causes the exception, and then the information.\n",
    "\n",
    "PS: In more complex programs the information about the exception can be very long (tip: in this case start reading from the bottom up).\n",
    "\n",
    "As you can see the type of exception appears in red <span style=\"color:red\">ZeroDivisionError</span>. We will see the most frequent exceptions and how to treat them as the course progresses. \n",
    "\n",
    "### <span style=\"color:green\">Finally let's look at semantic errors.</span>\n",
    "\n",
    "A program is written to calculate the length of the circle of radius 4 (the formula should be 2 * Pi * radius)\n",
    "\n",
    "Now if we write in the next cell print (3.14159 * 4) instead of (2* 3.14159 * 4), this will cause a semantic error. "

    "## <span style=\"color:blue\"> 5. Literal values (quotes) and data types\n",
    "\n",
    "In <b> print () </b> statements that we have used, some has appeared written in <span style=\"color:red\"> red </span>. When does the editor mark a part of a statement in red?\n",
    "\n",
    "It does when it is a literal/quote, when it is a string. Quotes are texts written between quotation marks. We use them when assigning a fixed value that we dont want to change. \n",
    "However we also need to edit and modify data sometimes even during the execution of a program, that when we need to use Variables.\n",
    "\n",
    "Variables are memory spaces in which we store, modify, and read information again, etc. these memory spaces are referred to by the variable name.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 5.1 Data types.\n",
    "\n",
    "Variables can be of many different data types, depending on the type of information that we will need to store. In this first module we are going to use the following types:\n",
    "\n",
    "PS: The type() function returns the type of a variable."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "variable_string = \"Hello\"\n",
    "variable_int = 35\n",
    "variable_float = 3.45\n",
    "variable_bool = True\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "print (\"variable_string, its type is \",type(variable_string))\n",
    "print (\"variable_int, its type is \",type(variable_int))\n",
    "print (\"variable_float,  its type is \",type(variable_float))\n",
    "print (\"variable_bool,  its type is \",type(variable_bool))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<span style=\"color:green\">As always, some details:</span>\n",
    "\n",
    "We can assign a literal to the string variables; it will appear in red when surrounded by quotes.\n",
    "\n",
    "The numbers (int or float) appear in green.\n",
    "\n",
    "The two boolean values appear in green and bold. They must be written with capital letters: True and False."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### <span style=\"color:green\">And of course, some details:</span>\n",
    "\n",
    "If you've used other programming languages, you'll remember type declarations. In Python we dont need to decare the data type before we use variables, it is contextual. The interpreter assigns a type to the variables according to the context, and it can also change during the execution of the program.\n",
    "\n",
    "variable_1 was integer, but when dividing it by 4 Python then changes its type to float.\n",
    "\n",
    "variable_4 is a string, it is the character that represents the number 2, not the number. Run the following cell and read the information about the exception that is thrown.\n",
    "\n",
    "The variables variable_5 and variable_6 could have been integers. But by writing .0 we have specified that we want variable_5 to be float, and so did variable_6."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,

    "## <span style=\"color:blue\">6. Expressions, Operators and Sentences</span>\n",
    "\n",
    "An **expression** is a combination of **values**, **variables**, **operators** and **function calls**\n",
    "\n",
    "In the next cell, the variables expression_1, expression_2 and expression_3 are assigned to the results of the results of the operations. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "expresion_1 = 1+4\n",
    "expresion_2 = len(\"Hola\")\n",
    "x = 3\n",
    "expresión_3 = 3 * x"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### <span style=\"color:blue\">6.1 Operators.</span>\n",
    "\n",
    "<b>Operators are special symbols that perform operations on variables and values. For example, print(10 + 3). Here, + is an operator that adds two numbers: 5 and 6.</b>\n",
    "\n",
    "The first operator is the assignment operator \"=\" and we have already used it in the previous cells.\n",
    "\n",
    "Get used to reading it as **assign**, do not read as equal to, that will help you internalize that it is not a mathematical expression but it is an operation that assigns value to the variable that is on the left of the expression.\n",
    "\n",
    "Run the following cell:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "x = 3\n",
    "x = 2\n",
    "x = x+5\n",
    "x+1 = 3"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "An exception occurred on the last line! why? \n",
    "\n",
    "If you read like in math:\n",
    "             x equals 3\n",
    "             x is equal to 2 (that is incorrect because what do we end up with is equal to two or three? In mathematics this second expression is incorrect\n",
    "             X equals X plus five. (Also incorrect, impossible)\n",
    "             X plus one equals three (finally something that makes sense, X is equal to 2 and Python goes and gives an error)\n",
    "            \n",
    "In programming it actually reads:\n",
    "             I assign the value 3 to x\n",
    "             Now I assign the value 2 to X\n",
    "             Now I assign to x (previously stored value) plus 5 to X\n",
    "             Uhmmm to the left of the assignment sign there should be a variable, not an expression.\n",
    "            \n",
    "In mathematics the expressions a = b and b = a are the same expression. Not in programming!!! The first expression assigns the variable to the value that b has at that moment and forgets what was in a. The second forgets what was in b because that variable stores the value of a.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {
    "803ecff7-0bd4-4913-9523-d4af99e42495.png": {
     "image/png": ""
    }
   },
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### <span style=\"color:blue\">6.1.1 Arithmetic operators.</span>\n",

    "\n",
    "\n",
    "To learn more details (especially formal) about these operations, visit following the page\n",
    "\n",
    "https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#numeric-types-int-float-complex"
   ]

   "source": [
    "### <span style=\"color:red\">Practical Exercise</span>\n",
    "\n",
    "using these two operators: Integer division // and remainder or modulo %.\n",
    "Let's solve the following exercise:\n",
    "\n",
    "A class of 35 students, there are teams of 3. How many teams are there and how many students are unpaired?\n",
    "Similar to the previous exercise fill XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX and do not modify the print() function. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],

    "print (n*a < a+b)\n",
    "print (a>b)\n",
    "print (\"ñ\" < \"p\")\n",
    "print (\"Ñ\" < \"p\")\n",
    "print (\"x\" < \"2\")\n",
    "print (b < \"zzz\")\n",
    "print (\"x\" < n)"

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### <span style=\"color:green\">If you got them all right, you pay attention to the details</span>\n",
    "\n",
    "If not, you will have to pay more attention to details.\n",
    "\n",
    "An exception has occurred, we will talk about it later, we go in order because the rest of the print () were executed correctly before the exception occurred.\n",
    "\n",
    "A is before D, therefore True\n",
    "\n",
    "The m is not after the p, False\n",
    "\n",
    "The value of the variable a is \"A\", therefore True\n",
    "\n",
    "The value of variable a is different from that of variable b, therefore True\n",
    "\n",
    "Lowercase letters come alphabetically after uppercase letters, then False\n",
    "\n",
    "2 * a is \" A A\" and the juxtaposition of \"a\" and \"b\" is \" A b\" the first three characters are the same and the capital letter before the lower case, True\n",
    "\n",
    "a is \"A\" and b is \"b\", capital letters first then False.\n",
    "\n",
    "The ñ does not go before the p, it is after the rest of the letters, False\n",
    "\n",
    "The \"Ñ\" does not go before p either, even though it is capital it is after the rest of the letters, so True\n",
    "\n",
    "Numbers come before letters, False\n",
    "\n",
    "The variable \"b\" begins with a space, and the space comes before the letters, True\n",
    "\n",
    "Exception: Python does not support a comparison between strings and integers.\n"
   ]
  },

    "## <span style=\"color:blue\"> 7. Variable names\n",
    "    \n",
    "Python is very flexible when it comes to naming our variables.\n",
    "\n",
    "A variable name can contain letters, digits or “_”, but cannot start with digits.\n",
    "\n",
    "![variableAndContants.png](attachment:97f5c79e-6a82-4af1-9080-e1d9973a25a6.png)\n",
    "    \n",
    "However, there are rules (conventions) that will help you make your programs more understandable (for yourself and others).\n",
    "    \n",
    "Conventions for this course:\n",
    "    \n",
    "     The variable names should be descriptive.\n",
    "     Variable names are nouns (Except from boolean).\n",
    "     You can use upper or/and lower cases as you wish, however it has to be consistent for your entire program.\n",
    "     You can use numbers or/and underscore _  as you wish, however it has to be consistent for your entire program.\n",
    "     Never use special Python words (those that appear in green) as variable names.\n",
    "     Do not use ñ or other stressed vowels in the names of your variables.\n",
    "    "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### <span style=\"color:green\">Python is case-sensitive</span>\n",
    "\n",
    "This means that name, Name and NAME are three different variables."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "Nombre = \"Alfredo\"\n",
    "nombre = \"Betina\"\n",
    "NOMBRE = \"Cristina\"\n",
    "\n",
    "print (Nombre,nombre,NOMBRE)"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",

    "## <span style=\"color:blue\"> 8. Operators. Order.\n",
    "\n",
    "<b>When there are more than one operator in an expression, the precedence rules must be taken into account:</b>\n",
    "\n",
    "In a complex expression, with comparators, juxtapositions, mathematical operations, what is the order in which these operator are executed?\n",
    "\n",
    "Keep in mind that running one operator before or after the other may change the output results.\n",
    "\n",
    "<b>Basic rule: If you have doubts, you can mark the operator that you want to execute first using parentheses, because parentheses have the highest priority. </b>\n",
    "    \n",
    "In the following link you have the table with the priorities (precedence). It includes elements of Python that we have not yet studied, and it is not easy to remember them all. Again, if you are not clear, you can parentheses.\n",
    "\n",
    "https://docs.python.org/3/reference/expressions.html#operator-precedence"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": []
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## <span style=\"color:blue\"> 9. Comments\n",
    "\n",
    "<b>To add notes to your code (text that do not compile or run) you can use comments</b>\n",
    "\n",
    "### Types of comments: \n",
    "\n",
    "There are three types of comments: single-line, and multi-line comments. The syntax of comments varies depending on the type.\n",
    "    \n",
    "-Single-line: use symbol “#” \n",
    "    \n",
    "-Multi-line: use symbol \"\"\" at the beginning and at end of the block, it can be marked with \" or with `.\n",
    "    \n",
    "### <span style=\"color:red\"> Practical Example"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# This line does nothing\n",
    "\n",
    "pi = 3.14159\n",
    "\n",
    "\"\"\"Everything that is in red\n",
    "it's a comment and it is not executed\n",
    "I could have 'other' quotes\n",
    "\"\"\"\n",
    "print(pi)\n",
    "\n",
    "'''\n",
    "And the same thing happens here\n",
    "\"can I\" use the other one\n",
    "'''\n",
    "print(pi)\n",
    "\n",
    "pi = 12 # Be careful, I have done something crazy here, the variable called pi is no longer worth pi\n",
    "\n",
    "print(pi)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In reality some comments have a special meaning, but they are never executable in the instruction sequence.\n",
    "\n",
    "The # with some formats can indicate changes in the environment and the triple quotes in a function indicate the content of the help (), as we will see later in this course. The important thing now is that they are not executed when you press run.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## <span style=\"color:blue\"> 10. Data input and output\n",
    "\n",
    "<b> Basic input: enter any data from your keyboard </b>\n",
    "    \n",
    "### <span style=\"color:green\">Input function"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "age = input(\"Please enter your age: \")\n",
    "print (\"The variable age is valid\",age,\"and is of type\",type(age))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "print (5)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {
    "47575910-e438-4645-901e-dd850397a1da.png": {
     "image/png": ""
    },
    "acd30c20-7967-42ed-97ea-885075337ef8.JPG": {
     "image/jpeg": ""
    }
   },
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "jp-MarkdownHeadingCollapsed": true
   },
   "source": [
    "### <span style=\"color:green\">Have you noticed the following details? </span>\n",
    "    \n",
    "The input() function has only one parameter, we don't need to specify the type of the parameter. \n",
    "  \n",
    "The result of the function is always a string. So how do I ask for a number? well you can't, you have to ask for a string and convert it (using **int()** function).\n",
    "    \n",
    "In Jupyter notebooks, every time there is an input() a small box opens below the code cell for you to type, it will close when you press enter. Additionally, an asterisk will appear in the execution counter, which will only disappear when you press enter. Make sure you click the input box before you start typing.\n",
    "![inputFunctionAsterick.png](attachment:47575910-e438-4645-901e-dd850397a1da.png)\n",
    "\n",
